We can use `vmstat` to check the virtual memory statistics.

In ostep-homework, there's a C program called `mem.c` that we need to compile
into `mem` executable to measure the virtual memory usage.

Let's say we have swap space and 16 GB of memory with 15 GB available memory,
and then we use `mem 8000` (basically allocate 8000 MB or 8 GB of data). In that
scenario, the loop 0 will take longer time (1413.24 ms, bandwidth: 5660.77 MB/s)
than the loop 1 (944.62 ms, bandwidth: 8469.01 MB/s), and so on. And also we
didn't use any swap space.

Let's say we have swap space and 16 GB of memory with 15 GB available memory,
and then we use `mem 16000` (basically allocate 16000 MB or 16 GB of data, more
than the available memory). In that scenario, the loop 0 will take less time
(4253.66 ms, bandwidth: 3761.47 MB/s) than loop 1
(23816.21 ms, bandwidth: 671.81 MB/s), and so on. And also we use the swap space
around 10 GB (according to `grep SwapCached /proc/meminfo`). Still not sure why
we use that much swap space when we have 15 GB available memory, possibly because
the `MemAvailable` from `/proc/meminfo` is not enough to store the data (?).
This is also the first time I see `MemAvailable` (40776 kB) is less than
`MemFree` (129532 kB), which is interesting.
